Eighth Wonder of the World is an unofficial title sometimes given to new buildings, structures, projects, or even designs that are deemed to be comparable to the seven Wonders of the World.

Candidates for the Eighth Wonder of the World[edit]

Mitre Peak, in Milford Sound, New Zealand

Natural places[edit]

  • Burney Falls in California; called so by Theodore Roosevelt[1]
  • Deadvlei Clay Pan in Namibia[2]
  • Giant's Causeway in County Antrim, Northern Ireland[citation needed]
  • Gros Morne National Park in Newfoundland, Canada[3]
  • Milford Sound in New Zealand; called so by Rudyard Kipling[4]
  • Natural Bridge (Virginia), so dubbed by William Jennings Bryan[5]
  • Niagara Falls, between the province of Ontario and the state of New York.[6]
  • The Okavango Delta in Botswana[citation needed]
  • Pink and White Terraces in New Zealand, prior to their wrongly assumed destruction in the 1886 eruption of Mount Tarawera.[7] In 2017 researchers using a lost 1959 survey finally mapped the Pink and White terrace locations.[8][9]
  • Torres del Paine National Park, Chile.[10][11]
  • The great wildebeest migration in the Maasai Mara, Kenya and Serengeti, Tanzania[12]
  • Uluru in Australia.[citation needed]

Pre-1900 creations[edit]

Sigiriya in Matale District, Sri Lanka
Angkor Wat in Angkor, Cambodia
The Citadelle Laferrière in Northern Haiti
Monolithic church of Ethiopia in Lalibela, Ethiopia
  • Amber Room in the Catherine Palace near Saint Petersburg, Russia[13]
  • Angkor Wat, Cambodia[14]
  • Banaue Rice Terraces, Philippines[15][16][17][18][19][20]
  • Borobudur, in Magelang, Indonesia,[21]
  • Capilla de Nuestra Señora del Rosario, Puebla City, Mexico[22]
  • The Citadelle Laferrière, Haiti[23]
  • The Eads Bridge, St. Louis, Missouri[24]
  • El Escorial monastery of San Lorenzo, Spain.[25]
  • The Forth Railway Bridge in Scotland[26]
  • Great Wall of China, China[27]
  • The original 1882 Kinzua Viaduct (railway bridge) in US.
  • Machu Picchu, Peru[28]
  • The moai statues of Easter Island, Chile[29]
  • The Obelisk of Axum, Ethiopia[30]
  • The rock-hewn churches at Lalibela, Ethiopia[31] (Church of Saint George, Lalibela)
  • Royal Palace in Amsterdam, Netherlands[32]
  • Sigiriya, Sri Lanka[33][34][35]
  • Statue of Liberty, New York Harbor, United States[36]
  • Stonehenge, United Kingdom[37]
  • The Taj Mahal, India[38][39]
  • The Terracotta Army, China[40]
  • The original rail-only Victoria Bridge (Montreal).[41]

Post-1900 creations[edit]

  • Aswan Dam in Egypt, called as such by Nikita Khrushchev[42]
  • Bahá'í terraces, on Mount Carmel, Haifa, Israel.[43]
  • Delta Works, the Dutch provinces of Zeeland and Zuid-Holland, the Netherlands. The Delta Works has been called one of the Seven Wonders of the Modern World by Quest magazine and the American Society of Civil Engineers, and the "Eighth Wonder of the World" by several other sources.[44]
Sydney Opera House, Sydney, Australia
  • Empire State Building, New York City.[45][46]
  • Great Manmade River in Libya; given the title by Muammar Gaddafi.[47]
  • Hibernia Oil Platform[48]
  • Houston Astrodome[49]
  • International Space Station in Orbit around Earth; title given by the Americans and Russians.[citation needed]
  • Karakoram Highway in Pakistan, and China
  • Palm Islands of Dubai[50]
  • Panama Canal[51]
  • Pikeville Cut-Through in Pikeville, Kentucky; given the title by The New York Times.[52][53][54]
  • Sydney Opera House in Sydney, Australia;[55] the story of its construction was recounted in the opera The Eighth Wonder
  • Thames Barrier, London, United Kingdom.[56]
  • Three Gorges Dam in Hubei, China[57]
  • West Baden Springs Hotel[58]

Popular culture[edit]

  • King Kong, a fictional giant movie monster resembling a colossal gorilla, that has appeared in several movies since 1933. His captor promotes public exhibitions of the caged Kong with the tagline: "Eighth Wonder of the World".[59]
  • Similarly, Gorgo, a fictional 65-foot tall dinosaur-like creature captured of the coast of the fictitious Irish isle of Nara Island from the British kaiju film of the same name is promoted as the "8th Wonder of the World" while on display at a circus in London. [60]
  • André the Giant, a French professional wrestler and actor in the 1970s and 1980s, who was billed as being 7 ft 4 in (2.24 m) and 500 lb (230 kg), was regularly referred to as the Eighth Wonder of the World by the World Wrestling Federation (WWF).
  • Foxconn Factory being constructed in Wisconsin that Donald Trump was quoted as describing as "the eighth wonder of the world." [61]
